Named after a Swedish mining town, this village is home to one of the region's largest prisons, grimly called 'Frozen Hell' by its inhabitants. Shortly after the outbreak, the prison was abandoned, leaving the inmates' fate unknown.

A hamlet located in the Adirondack Mountains. Lyon Mountain once thrived on its booming mining industry. Since operations ceased in the late 60s, the town's vibrancy has faded, leaving its abandoned mines dormant, daring only the bold — or foolish — to explore.
A small, loosely connected, rural hamlet with a couple small business and mostly single family housing. There weren't many people here before the apocalypse, and now there are far fewer.

Often mistaken for Saranac Lake, NY, this small, elongated town is home to numerous small businesses and government buildings. Its school, the district's largest, emerged as a primary refuge for locals in the region when the apocalypse struck the valley.
A quiet, idyllic farm located well away from urban centers. The owner was well-prepared and well-stocked, but seems to have vanished. No zombies here... unless?

Recommended for players that are either new to VEIN or other survival games.
A harder experience to keep you on your toes. Recommended to players who are either experienced with VEIN or other survival games.
A difficult and frustrating experience that’s tailored to the players who enjoy suffering.
Recommended for players who are new to games in general or want very relaxed combat.
A middle-of-the-road experience that has plenty downtime with some challenge mixed in. This is our preferred way to play VEIN.
A hard, and sometimes unfair, experience that’s recommended for players who really want a challenge and don’t mind occasional frustrations.

Translated: 50% in meno di stanchezza quando si salta.

Original: You get 30% as tired while sprinting.
Continuing to sprint while 100% tired no longer causes pain.
You take 50% as much fall damage. However, lethal fall damage is still lethal.
You can move 50% faster while crouching.
You can jump slightly higher than normal.
Can build scrap wood fortifications without the use of any tools.
You can see the exact health points of doors, fortifications, etc. and their weaknesses, if applicable.
Cost of crafting reinforced wood fortifications is reduced by 25%.
Cost of crafting limestone fortifications is reduced by 10%.
While stimulated, do 1.5x the damage with tools that double as melee weapons.
Eating raw ingredients, such as sugar or flour, satisfy your hunger 25% more.
The negative effects of consuming cooked human flesh are reduced by 25%.
Your chances of becoming sick from eating raw meat are reduced by 50%.
As your nearby Utility Cabinet becomes more full, your stress decreases.
All schematics, regardless of what skill it’s for, give 25% more XP when read.
All Standard Workbench recipes are 50% cheaper to craft.
All schematics, regardless of what skill it’s for, have their stat level requirement reduced by 5.
Can use a cutting tool with the tier below the recipe’s stated requirement. (If the recipe normally requires heavy cutting, basic cutting can be used instead, etc.)
You have a 15% chance of receiving double the amount of items when crafting.
When crafting an item, you have a rare chance that you won’t use your ingredients.
Removes the Basic Cutting tool requirement for furniture that requires it.
When dismantling, have a 1/4 chance to receive 25% more yield than you normally would.
Dismantling items reduces stress, and dismantling furniture reduces it more.
Smaller civilian vehicles use 50% less gasoline.
Rainy or stormy weather no longer negatively affects your traction. Does not apply to blizzards or snow.
Batteries in your inventory drain half as fast.
Discarding a growing plant gives you a 50% chance of recovering its seed.
You can see how long it will take a compost bin to create soil as well as the quality of soil it will yield.
XP gained by related skill tasks is increased by 25%.
Dead plants continue to grow very slowly.
Skill books give one extra stat level.
Lockpicking a door connected to a door alarm has a high chance to not trigger the alarm.
You can inspect a corpse and see how it died.
Get the ability to see other players' approximate health.
Get the ability to see other players' exact health.
10% likelier to find rare items while scavenging.
The chances of causing floor creaks are reduced by 50%.
The noise you make is generally reduced by 25%.
Gain 50 lbs/22.7 kg of carry weight.
You can dismantle furniture and items that normally require a powered cutting tool with a heavy cutting tool.
There is a rare chance that if you get hit by an item, it goes in your inventory.
Throwing large items (like printers) at someone's head deals 150% consciousness damage.
The chance of dirty bandages becoming infected is reduced 25%.
Your max health is increased by 25%.
Your chances of getting sick are tripled, and the effects are stronger, but you get a 5% XP bonus in every skill.
50% as likely to get broken arms and legs.
You can reload magazines 1.3x as fast.
You can load 3 bullets at a time into a firearm magazine.
The fire rate of ranged weapons is reduced by 15% but is more accurate.
Your creativity when combining unrelated items.

Original: Your weight lifting capacity, melee damage, and knockback chance.
Your performance hitting targets with objects.
Your persuasion towards getting good deals.
You lost your {Item}. We've given you a new one just in case.
It seems like you know what you're doing. Good luck!
Would you like to exit to the main menu?

You're injured, and need to find some supplies.

Head to the <B>house</>.

The door is locked. You'll have to head through the window.

Press <B>{RaiseFistsKey}</> to raise your fists, and <B>{PrimaryKey}</> to punch the window.
Did you see the canteen in the dresser? That might be handy. Take it from the dresser.

You have some space in your new canteen. Go to the sink and select Fill Container.

Select the canteen when it appears to fill it.

Why not take a drink?

Select the canteen in your inventory, and drink from it by clicking the appropriate option.

In VEIN, you have conditions like thirst that some items can satisfy. Just beware that things are not always as they seem - and a water bottle may not contain water!

Uh oh! Looks like the power just went out.

Grab a flashlight from the nearby shelves.

Equip your new flashlight.

You can do this by double clicking the item, or by dragging it onto one of your equipment slots at the bottom of your inventory page.

Press <B>{FlashlightKey}</> to toggle your flashlight.

Now that you can see, turn on the power by going to the generator outside.

Pick up the spare gas canister. Look at the generator, and in your inventory, select the gas canister. Pour it into the generator through the inventory screen to start it up again.

The generator looks to be running! Now turn on the fuse box inside the bedroom.

Power, water, and many other systems in VEIN are connected to a real grid, so if there are any fuse boxes or junction boxes that are switched off, power will be disrupted.

Looks like that did it. Now let's fortify our cabin.

Look at some furniture and select Destroy to break it into parts.

A utility cabinet marks an area as yours. Other players can't search nearby one, unlock locks, etc. unless you give them permission or they break it down. In addition, zombies don't appear near them.

Press <B>{ConstructionKey}</> to open your construction menu.

Go to the Utility Cabinets tab. Select a utility cabinet then click Build in the left menu.

Place it somewhere by pressing and holding <B>{PrimaryKey}</>.

Let's fortify the door. In the same way as you built a utility cabinet, select a Scrap Wood Door and build it on top of the existing door.

In VEIN, fortifications usually fortify existing building elements.

There are blinds in the way.

Use your scroll wheel to scroll to "Up", then hold <B>{UseKey}</> to move them.

Same thing, but a Scrap Wood Window now. Build a window in the cabin's window.

Good thing we have a utility cabinet - without it, our fortifications will decay and break.
Now that we're defended, let's get offensive. Grab a <B>baseball bat</>.

Now open the workbench.

Move the baseball bat, nails, and hammer from your inventory to the repair bench's inventory.

Search for "spike" in the recipe list and you should be able to craft a spiked baseball bat by selecting the recipe.

Wait for the crafting to finish, then take the nail baseball bat from the workbench into your inventory.

We'll pin the baseball bat now.

<B>Close</> the workbench UI.

Click the bat in your inventory and click <B>Add to Quick Use</>. This lets you use number keys to quickly equip the baseball bat.

Finally, close your inventory and hit <B>{Slot1Key}</> to equip the bat.
You might have seen the <B>car</> outside. Let's see if it works.
Let's check the condition. Look at the <B>hood of the car</> and open it up.

You can click on parts to see more information about them.

The <B>battery</> is dead. Let's see if we can find a new one in the garage.

Grab the <B>battery</> from the shelf, and take a <B>screwdriver</>.

If the battery's too heavy, you might need to drop some items by dragging them out of your inventory or moving them somewhere else.

Go back to the car, and open the hood.

Select the car battery and click <B>Uninstall and Drop Part</> to remove it.

Jump and crouch through the window to enter.

It's dark! Switch on the light.

Look at the light switch on the wall, then press <B>{UseKey}</> to turn it on.
Drag the car battery from your inventory into the newly emptied slot to install it.

Uh oh... Sounds like you've been noticed.

Kill all the zombies to proceed.

Use <B>{PrimaryKey}</> to strike. Hold and release it to do a power attack. Right click or press <B>{QuickMeleeKey}</> to shove.

Close one!

Get in the vehicle by using its driver-seat door.
Start the car by looking at the ignition and holding <B>{UseKey}</>.

Let's get out of here.

The tutorial ends here, but you're welcome to play around with what you've done so far.
Hold <B>{UseKey}</> while looking at the shards to clear them.

It's cold in here and you need to warm up.

Turn on the radiator by scrolling to Turn On in its options, and pressing <B>{UseKey}</>.

You're injured and need to treat your injury. Get a <B>splint</> from the medical pack.

Look at the pack and press <B>{UseKey}</> to open it.

You can move things between inventories by dragging the item or by shift-clicking.

To use your new splint, select the item by clicking on it. Then in the use options near the bottom, click Treat Injury.

If you accidentally close your inventory press <B>{InventoryKey}</> to open it back up again.

You don't have any clothes. Maybe you can find some dry ones in the bedroom.

Check the dresser with your <B>{UseKey}</>.

Close the container inventory.

Open your own inventory with <B>{InventoryKey}</> and equip your new shirt.

You can do this by dragging the item on a clothing slot, by double-clicking the item, or by clicking Equip in the shirt's use options.
Destroys what you're looking at forever! (If this is disabled, you can't destroy this).
